***
[2
Date: Sun 9 Jan 2000
From: Daniel S. Shapiro <dshapiro@bu.edu>

The transmission of Q-fever to humans has also been attributed to ticks on
imported reptiles, in this case from snakes.
Reference:
Q fever-- New York. MMWR 1978 27:321
***
[3
Date: Sun 9 Jan 2000
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj@mail.vetmed.lsu.edu>

Owners regularly abandon pets, even expensive imported exotics, and in
Florida, with its welcoming semi-tropical environment, the risks of also
releasing tropical _Amblyomma_ spp. (the original script never specifically
said _A. variegatum_ but it was strongly implied) may be in the "probable"
range.
We would welcome comments from APHIS on this matter.
--
Martin Hugh-Jones
Department of Epidemiology & Community Health,
School of Veterinary Medicine,
Louisiana State University,
Baton Rouge, LA 70803, USA
tel: (225) 346-3341
fax: (225) 346-3331
email: mehj@mail.vetmed.lsu.edu
